&quot;It's early days yet and it will take time to plot its direction. As yet we only have a location in the sky. We will have to wait until it has moved to make precise predictions. At this point I would say there is only a 1 in 10,000 chance of impact. It will more than likely pass between the Earth and moon, back past the Sun and not return again for a couple of generations minimum. We have nothing resembling this object recorded in historical archives so I'm assuming it is on a wide orbit which rarely brings it back this way. It might possibly be a belt object which was thrown into a strange orbit millions of years ago by Jupiter. It might not pass our way again for thousands of years even.&quot;<br>
