 the appearance of tumbling through space.  After going through the trouble of stopping the asteroid from tumbling.  Now, here the doosy.  You see, most asteroids aren't in one single piece.  Most asteroids are just a collection of gravel and dirt held barely together by gravity.  This is due to the fact that most asteroids suffer catastropic collisions that breaks them apart and gravity pulls some of the pieces back together.  This happens repeatedly.  Any attempt to apply a large amount of thrust to the surface results in tearing the asteroid apart with most of it still heading towards earth.  An alternative is nuking the asteroid.  The way you destroy a celestrial body is by giving enough kinetic energy to the matter in a celestrial object to surpass its own escape velocity.  I calculate that it will take 672 billion joules of energy to destroy an asteroid one cubic kilometer in volume with an average density of 2500 kg/m^3.  Even on the assume that only 1% of the nuclear bomb's energy is converted to kinetic energy for the asteroid fragments, all it will take to destroy an asteroid is one 14 kiloton bomb.  More than likely, at least 10% of the energy will be converted to kinetic energy.  But won't that just spread the damage over a larger area?  Not if you destroy the asteroid far enough away.  If you give the fragments an average velocity of 10 m/s away from its center of mass, which will remain constant, the debris will spread out at a radius of 63 thousands kilometers in a period of 3 months, which is ten times the earth's radius.  This would cause most of the debris to miss the earth all together.  Any pieces too large to burn up in the atmosphere can be destroyed by smaller nukes.  In order for this work, the detonation must take place in the center of the asteroid.  Ether, a probe could be sent ahead of time to examine the asteroid for soft spots for a missile to burrow into the asteroid using a method similar to bunker buster proposed by the DoD.  The other method is use a small nuclear reactor that will deliberately go into meltdown on the surface and melt its way to the center, and after a few days, the nuke will go down the hole. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1050<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/2/02 10:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Last Hope.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> A bit cheesy, isn't it?  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
